76561198080467957,Recommended,251470,25787864,"Posted: 30 September, 2016",all,Tiny Rick,wanna be more♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥off at your friends than you've ever been? play this game couch coop. 10/10 would be mad again.
,Recommended,251470,27347655,"Posted: 24 November, 2016",all,Anzhou,"This is a game that you HAVE to play with other people.  Its single player mode is tacked on and hollow (much like many modern games). I cannot recommend it if you're looking for a good single player experience. However, its incredible multiplayer more than justifies the game's reasonable asking price if you have a few controllers. While the Dark World expansion fleshes out the campaign, it is still best enjoyed when you have a few friends to share in the rage. One MAJOR caveat: the game has no online multiplayer. While the reasoning is understandable, (the game has mechanics timed down to individual frames and would be a subpar experience if there's any amount of latency involved) I believe having a poor online mode would still be superior to not having one at all.Barring those few criticisms, Towerfall Ascension is a gem of a local multiplayer brawler. You play as one of several archers (that vary only cosmetically) and have a limited number of arrows (3 by default). Once you shoot an arrow, it is left on the world and you must pick it up by walking over it. Your movement and aiming is combined into a single control, which takes some getting used to if you're new to the genre. You are only able to move and aim in 8 principle directions. The arrows you shoot home slightly if there's an enemy in range, and there are multiple arrow types that range from exploding to bouncing to piercing. Each attack is an instant kill, regardless of whether it was through shooting your opponent with an arrow, hitting them with an arrow's secondary effect, or stomping their heads in. There is also dodging, which is both your defense and mobility ability. And finally, there is screen wrap, where the top/bottom and left/right of the screen are connected.It was designed from the ground up to be played locally, and accommodates both casual and competitive play. The default game mode on headhunter is perfect for people who have never played the game, with just enough rubber-banding to keep everyone in the game without being egregious (nothing like Mario Kart's first to worst from a single blue shell). Each round is paced well, and no one ever stays hopeless or dead for too long. You can go down the list of maps to gradually introduce your friends to new items, and never really overwhelm them (unless you want to).If you're playing casually with experienced players, custom game modes vastly increase the replayability of an already replayable game. Small tweaks like spawning with special arrows or returning as ghosts result in significant changes in how you play. And finally, making an asymmetric custom mode (2v1/3v1 team death match) where one player gets huge bonuses (such as regenerating shields and arrows) while the opposing team gets an advantage in numbers is almost like playing an entirely new game. Even the more chaotic game modes (like infinite drill arrows or infinite laser arrows) are good for a round or two before you abandon them and pretend they never existed.And finally, the game is very well balanced competitively. Dodge cancelling and superjumping are difficult mechanics to master, and yield a surprisingly high skill ceiling. While there are a few oddities for a competitive game (bolt arrows finding your opponent's home from 3 zipcodes away, kicking their dog, then brutally murdering them right in the face comes to mind) it's nothing that custom rules can't fix. Because everyone has the same attacks and abilities, the only thing that sets players apart is their positioning, skill, and reflexes.Towerfall Ascension is an amazing game that I highly recommend if and only if you play local multiplayer games. Do not buy this game if you're looking for a single player game or a good story (mediocre and nonexistent respectively). However, Towerfall Ascension is one of the best local multiplayer games out there. If you own a few controllers and have people over occasionally, this game is almost mandatory."
