,Recommended,251470,10272711,"Posted: 29 May, 2014",all,M_W,"Honestly, I have not had this much fun playing multiplayer of any kind since my childhood of playing MarioKart 64, Super Smash Bros. for the N64, and Halo 2. Towerfall: Ascension works equally well as a competetive experience and a casual party game--a feat not acheived since, arguably, Super Smash Bros. Melee.For the uninitiated: Towerfall: Ascension is a two-dimensional, single-screen, local-only multplayer game in which two to four players attempt to be the last person standing by launching volleys of arrows and squishing heads like an Italian plumber on a small mushroom creature. The mechanics are simple--providing you controls for moving, shooting, jumping, and dodging alone--but offer a level of depth I have barely begun to penetrate.If you want to really shake things up, though; Towerfall offers a crazy amount of variants, all of which can be combined in any configuration. Want infinite arrows? Got it. Exploding corpses? Got that, too. Exploding corpses that trigger on command of the deceased? Oh yeah, it's got that.Towerfall does offer single or multplayer Quest and Trials mode, which are very fun in their own right, and can be crazy addicting if you're looking to master the game, but the real meat and potatoes is in the competitive multplayer. So, if you don't have many friends to play with IRL, or enough controllers to acommodate them, give this one a pass, but if you want to relive the days of your childhood when you had your friends over to play Smash Bros., Goldeneye, MarioKart, et al, you cannot afford to miss this game.Do I recommend it? Hell yes."
